^d@e@2Puppet Stayman is a special version of Stayman that allows the responder to a NT opener to discover if opener @E@3has either a 4 card major (just like regular Stayman) or a 5 card major, and also allows the contract to be played by the opener, who has the stronger hand. Sometimes, opener will open either 1N or 2N (or 2@C followed by 2N) with a 5 card major, and Puppet allows responder to find the 5-3 fit in addition to the 4-4 fit. Many experts play Puppet Stayman over 2N (and 2C followed by 2N), and some even play it over 1N. However, it is somewhat complicated, and I do not feel it is necessary for less experienced players to use it.

Puppet Stayman works as follows. For this discussion, assume the opening bid is 2N. With either a 3 card major or a 4 card major, responder bids 3@C (Puppet Stayman).

If opener has neither a 5 card major nor a 4 card major, he bids 3N (not 3@D, as in regular Stayman). Responder now knows there is no possibility of a major suit fit.

Opener bids any 5 card major over 3@C. Responder can then either bid 4 of that major with 3+ card support, or 3N without support.

Opener bids 3@D with one or two 4 card majors. Here is where it gets a little tricky. If responder has both 4 card majors, he bids 4@D over 3@D, and opener bids his major (or chooses his best major if he has both). If responder has only one card major, then responder bids the other major. So, if responder has hearts he bids 3S, and if responder has spades he bids 3@H. The reason for this is responder wants to let opener be declarer, so responder does not want to mention the potential trump suit first, otherwise responder would be declarer. So, if responder bids 3@S over 3@D (showing 4 hearts), opener would bid 4@H with 4 hearts and otherwise bid 3N. Similarly, if responder bids 3H over 3@D (showing 4 spades), opener would bid 4@S with 4 spades and otherwise bid 3N.

